  "doc_id": "56108",
  "text": "The abundant shelf-dwelling species of nototheniid such as L. larseni, G. gibberifrons and Trematomus hansoni and all of the channichthyids (icefishes) became very scarce or absent in trawls conducted deeper than 400 m. The catches within these depths were dominated by two species of nototheniid, L. squamifrons and D. eleginoides, but was also characterised by the presence of the achiropsettid flatfish Mancopsetta maculata (Assemblage B). These results are in very close agreement with the [CITATION_1] study from the Prince Edward Islands that recorded D. eleginoides and L. squamifrons being the dominant species within the shallow slope assemblage. At the Prince Edward Island [CITATION_2] and in the high Antarctic region [CITATION_3] ) the highest diversity of the Nototheniidae has been recorded between 300 and 600 m. Whilst overall fish diversity was greatest at these depths at South Georgia, the greatest Nototheniidae diversity was actually recorded over the shelf (Assemblage A). The high diversity within Assemblage B results from it being a transitional region between the shelf and deeper slope communities and therefore having representatives of both.",
